    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-14T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-14T06:00:00-05:00" n="133"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">660F.116/135: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wright</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Praha</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-14T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 14, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 1:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3. Your telegram No. 50, December 29, 2 p.m. Notwithstanding ruling of the
                    National Bank, reported in my telegram 75, December 22, 11 a.m., and despatch
                    No. 1460 of December 19th of the Consul General,<note n="34" xml:id="d133fn34"
                        >Despatch not printed.</note> the Foreign Office now informs me in writing:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Referring to the respective inquiry of the American Legation it is [<hi
                                rend="italic">has</hi>] to be added that the stipulation[s] of
                            article No. 2, paragraph No. 4, of the said Agreement in case of a
                            direct business between the Czechoslovak importer and American exporter
                            find no application as long as the representative of the American firm
                            in Bremen looks after the correct delivery and transport only. The
                            decisive factor remains the question who issues the invoice.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Aide-mémoire</hi> states further that “The new way of payment
                    for the cotton imported from America is based upon the consideration that a
                    portion of the expenses connected with the import of this raw material consists
                    of payment in German marks—reichsmarks. Should, <pb facs="0243" n="167"
                        xml:id="pg_167"/> namely, the business transaction be arranged and done
                    through an agent of Bremen the said portion of reichsmarks contained in the
                    amount of invoice must necessarily be increased by the commission to be paid to
                    the German agent”, as reported in my aforementioned telegram.</p>
                <p>Full text by mail.<note n="35" xml:id="d133fn35">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wright</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
